article.description: Kevin Garnett scored five of his season-high 34 points in overtime and grabbed 22 rebounds as the Minnesota Timberwolves kept the Grizzlies winless with a 110-106 victory.
article.headline: Wolves need all Garnett's 34 points, 22 boards

images.name: Garnett_Kevin 021119 inline
images.caption: Kevin Garnett's huge night helped keep Memphis winless.

article.linkText: Garnett goes off; Wolves keep Grizzlies winless
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Despite working overtime, the Memphis Grizzlies emerged winless. Kevin Garnett had 34 points and 22 rebounds as the Minnesota Timberwolves denied the Grizzlies their first win, rallying for a 110-106 overtime victory Tuesday night. The Grizzlies, who led by five points in the fourth quarter, fell to 0-11 overall and 0-3 under Hubie Brown. Memphis lost in overtime for the second time. "If anybody has ever had a root canal, that was like two at one time,'' Saunders said. "I'm not going to say it was pretty.'' But the Timberwolves kept their composure in the fourth quarter, using 10 free throws in a 17-7 run that turned a five-point deficit into a 98-93 lead. Memphis scored the final five points of the fourth quarter to force overtime. Anthony Peeler's 3-pointer with 3:05 to play in the extra period gave the Wolves the lead for good, 104-102. The Wolves scored the next four points but needed two free throws from Kendall Gill with 16.7 seconds left to ice it. "That's a very good team,'' Garnett said of the Grizzlies, who also lost to the Timberwolves in Brown's debut Friday night. "Their record doesn't reflect how hard they play. They made it a dogfight tonight.'' Jason Williams led the Grizzlies with 14 points. Seven Memphis players scored in double figures. Minnesota looked to have the game in hand when Troy Hudson's jumper gave the Wolves a five-point lead with 1:06 to play. But Williams' three-point play cut the lead to two, and Stromile Swift's free throws with 18.6 seconds to play tied the score again. Gill's jumper from the right corner was long at the regulation buzzer. "We got a little tired, but we left everything out there and gave ourselves the opportunity to win,'' Memphis' Shane Battier said. "We'll get it done.'' Gary Trent added 19 points for Minnesota, and Joe Smith, activated from the injured list prior to the game, scored all 12 of his points in the second half. Smith, playing for the first time since straining his groin Oct. 4, gave the team a burst of energy and was tireless on the boards before fouling out late in regulation. Despite Smith's work, Memphis' bench outscored Minnesota's 49-19, and Brown used five reserves for much of the fourth quarter before returning to the starters late in the game. "The second unit ran out of gas,'' Brown said. "We wanted to get Jason back in, and he made the plays to get us to overtime.'' The Wolves have won nine straight against the Grizzlies. The Grizzlies led by as many as 14 points in the first half before the Wolves pulled to 53-50 at the break. Gill hit a 3-pointer just before the buzzer. Garnett had 21 points and 10 rebounds in the first half.

Game notes
The Wolves activated Smith from the injured list and placed guard Wally Szczerbiak on it. Szczerbiak is suffering from inflammation in his left foot, which he injured in the team's first preseason game on Oct. 8. Gill started in Szczerbiak's place. ... Minnesota, fifth in the NBA in scoring last season, has scored 100 points in only four of its first 12 games. ... The Grizzlies had losing streaks of 11 games or more in each of their first five seasons, but none in the last two seasons. The franchise record is 21, set in 1995-96. ... Last Friday, Minnesota held Pau Gasol to four points -- the second-lowest total of his career. Gasol had 12 points on Tuesday. ... Garnett's 18 defensive rebounds were one short of his franchise record set Nov. 7 against Milwaukee.
